 word list of adjectives and nouns with their etymological origin. The word list

39
00:03:36.840 --> 00:03:43.200
 is arranged in alphabetical order and looks similar to a modern dictionary.

40
00:03:43.200 --> 00:03:48.360
 The eleventh book delves into topics such as mankind, portents, and transformations.

41
00:03:48.360 --> 00:03:53.280
 St. Isidore describes the ages of human beings and the many parts of the human

42
00:03:53.280 --> 00:03:57.920
 body, including the soul. He also discusses strange phenomena and

43
00:03:57.920 --> 00:04:06.600
 creatures such as metamorphoses, satyrs, and sirens. Books 12 through 14 are about

44
00:04:06.600 --> 00:04:13.960
 the natural world. They discuss topics such as animals, atoms, natural phenomena,

45
00:04:13.960 --> 00:04:19.200
 and geography. On the subject of geography, St. Isidore describes the

46
00:04:19.200 --> 00:04:26.200
 world as being circular and composed of three continents, Europe, Asia, and Africa,

47
00:04:26.200 --> 00:04:32.679
 with a great ocean that surrounds them. The fifteenth book is about buildings and

48
00:04:32.679 --> 00:04:37.720
 fields. It discusses the cities of the ancient world and who founded them. It

49
00:04:37.720 --> 00:04:43.079
 also describes different kinds of buildings such as lighthouses, monasteries,

50
00:04:43.079 --> 00:04:48.279
 and fortifications. The agricultural section of the book discusses various

51
00:04:48.279 --> 00:04:55.119
 kinds of fields and rural infrastructure. The next book covers rocks and metals.

52
00:04:55.119 --> 00:05:01.839
 St. Isidore starts off by explaining dust, dirt, and other earthly materials. He then

53
00:05:01.839 --> 00:05:07.399
 moves on to talk about the various kinds of stones, gems, and glass. In the second

54
00:05:07.399 --> 00:05:11.839
 half of the book, St. Isidore discusses the various kinds of metals such as gold,

55
00:05:11.839 --> 00:05:19.559
 silver, bronze, tin, and electrum. Books 17 through 20 are about the human

56
00:05:19.559 --> 00:05:25.559
 civilization. They delve into topics such as agriculture, ships, tools, food,

57
00:05:25.559 --> 00:05:33.119
 war, and jurisprudence. Throughout the medieval period, etymologi was the most

58
00:05:33.119 --> 00:05:39.119
 widely used textbook. In fact, etymologi was so widely used that it often

59
